eased bone mineral density","Reduced insulin production","Impaired thyroid function","Increased risk of cardiovascular disease","Primary liver dysfunction"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most well-established direct health impact of air pollution is \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased risk of cardiovascular disease\u003C/strong\u003E. Fine particulate matter (PM2.5) and other pollutants can enter the bloodstream through the lungs, causing systemic inflammation, oxidative stress, and endothelial dysfunction that contribute to cardiovascular disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased bone mineral density\u003C/strong\u003E - While some studies suggest possible associations between air pollution and bone health, this is not a primary or well-established direct effect.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced insulin production\u003C/strong\u003E - Although air pollution may contribute to metabolic disorders, there is insufficient evidence for direct effects on insulin production.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpaired thyroid function\u003C/strong\u003E - While endocrine disruption has been studied in relation to certain pollutants, direct effects on thyroid function are not well-established.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary liver dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E - The liver is not considered a primary target organ for the direct effects of air pollutants.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther well-documented health impacts of air pollution include respiratory diseases, exacerbation of asthma, reduced lung function, and increased risk of lung cancer. The cardiovascular effects are mediated through systemic inflammation and oxidative stress triggered by fine particulate matter entering the circulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Short-term exposure to air pollution can cause respiratory symptoms, while long-term exposure increases risk of cardiovascular disease and lung cancer.","Air pollution particularly affects vulnerable populations including children, elderly, and those with pre-existing respiratory conditions.","Air pollution increases the risk of cardiovascular disease mainly by activating inflammatory pathways"],"references":["Air quality, energy and health. WHO. Available from: https://www.who.int/teams/environment-climate-change-and-health/air-quality-energy-and-health/health-impacts.","Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021.","Krittanawong C, Qadeer YK, Hayes RB, et al. PM2.5 and cardiovascular diseases: State-of-the-Art review. Int J Cardiol Cardiovasc Risk Prev. 2023;19:200217. Published 2023 Oct 12. doi:10.1016/j.ijcrp.2023.200217"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60770"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17016"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60770"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T15:32:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-29T15:33:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9706"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75262"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical me